            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-08-15T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-08-15T20:00:00-05:00" n="1145" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1145">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.91293/8–1645: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-16T08:00:00+07:00">August 16, 1945—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1364. Association of foreign correspondents in Chungking has expressed interest
                    in the cases of Berrigan and Isaacs, on two counts: (1) to ascertain reason for
                    action of Chinese Government, and (2) for clarification of regulations governing
                    activities of correspondents, for <pb facs="1491" n="1481" xml:id="pg_1481"/>
                    their own guidance. They asked if I would transmit a communication to the State
                    Department covering point 1 and I agreed to do so. To date it has not been
                    received.</p>
                <p>I have informed them that in view of the Chinese Government no issue of freedom
                    of the press is involved and that I had communicated to State Department on
                    behalf of Chinese Government last week (see Embassy’s telegram No. 1310, August
                    9, 9 a.m.) statement of that Government relative to point 1. I also informed
                    them of possibility that Chinese Government might desire to issue statement to
                    correspondents in Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
